`crates/ctx-summarize` is a crate that turns a set of source paths into `.ctx`/`rollup.ctx` files by driving an external LLM agent, usable either as a library (`runner::run`/`run_with_prompts`) or as the `ctx-summarize` binary. Depending on it gets you the whole leaf-up summarization pipeline plus its safety gates (ignore-scope matching and a `MAX_TARGETS` cost guard requiring `--approve`); it does not get you prompt content or model behavior, which are loaded from disk and external, respectively.

The crate has two top-level pieces: `src/`, which implements the pipeline (CLI parsing, orchestration, filesystem/agent trait seams, path-mirroring helpers, and the shared `SummError` enum), and `tests/`, which validates the pipeline's external contract — leaf-before-rollup write ordering, read-only intent files, and secrets/path-escape rejection — using hermetic fakes (`FakeFs`, `RecordingAgent`) rather than a real agent or filesystem. Any change to write ordering, ignore-scope enforcement, or error variants in `src/` should be checked against the corresponding test in `tests/summarize.rs`, since that file is what pins the contract down.

The `.ctx`/`rollup.ctx` mirror-path convention and the gitignore-style scope matcher are the two subtree-spanning invariants that external callers (and `ctx-scan`) rely on; both are defined once in `src/` and exercised end-to-end by `tests/`.

